Here's a simple implementation of a function that converts markdown to HTML using the `std::string` and `std::regex` libraries in C++. This implementation supports basic markdown syntax for bold, italic, headers, links, and images.

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <regex>
#include <iostream>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;

    // Replace bold text
    std::regex markdownBoldRegex("~~~?\\*(.*?)\\*~~?");
    std::string replacementBold = "<b>$1</b>";
    html = std::regex_replace(markdown, markdownBoldRegex, replacementBold);

    // Replace italic text
    std::regex markdownItalicRegex("~~~?(.*?)~~?");
    std::string replacementItalic = "<i>$1</i>";
    html = std::regex_replace(html, markdownItalicRegex, replacementItalic);

    // Replace headers
    std::regex markdownHeaderRegex("^#{1,6} (.*)$", std::regex::ECMAScript);
    std::string replacementHeader = "<h$1>$2</h$1>";
    html = std::regex_replace(html, markdownHeaderRegex, replacementHeader, std::regex_constants::format_all, 1, std::sub_match<const char*>());

    // Replace links
    std::regex markdownLinkRegex("~~~?\\[(.*?)\\]\\((.*?)\\)~~?");
    std::string replacementLink = "<a href=\"$2\">$1</a>";
    html = std::regex_replace(html, markdownLinkRegex, replacementLink);

    // Replace images
    std::regex markdownImageRegex("~~~?\\!(.*?)\\(~?(.*?))~~?");
    std::string replacementImage = "<img src=\"$2\" alt=\"$1\"$3>";
    html = std::regex_replace(html, markdownImageRegex, replacementImage);

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Hello **bold** and *italic*\n"
                          "[Visit Google](https://www.google.com)\n"
                          "![](https://www.google.com/images/logo.png)\n"
                          "### This is a header";
    std::cout << markdownToHtml(markdown) << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This code uses `std::regex_replace` to replace markdown patterns with their HTML equivalents. The replacement strings use the captured groups from the regex pattern to insert the matched text into the replacement string.

Please note that this is a basic implementation and does not support all markdown features. You may need to add more patterns and replacement strings depending on your specific requirements.

Also, the regex patterns and replacement strings assume that the input markdown is well-formed, i.e., correctly formatted and without any invalid characters. You may want to add error handling to deal with invalid input.

